                  </persName>
            . I live in Nelson-street, and was present at the prisoner's marriage with Langham; I angham is now living with my sister as his wife.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-98-person881">
                  JANE 
                  EAGLES
               <interp inst="t18281204-98-person881" type="surname" value="EAGLES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-98-person881" type="given" value="JANE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-98-person881" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I have heard the prisoner say before Langham, that she was married before their marriage - I thought it was a romance of her's to say she was married; I do not know any thing of Wood; I saw him at Worship-street: I suppose he is fifty years of age.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I married Langham; for the last four months he has lived with that woman - he has used me ill; I threw myself into the canal, and, unfortunately, a bargeman took me out; Langham knew every thing about this; he said, "Go away, you can get your living at service;" I said, "If I go away I will leave my country;" I met him in Bishopsgate-street; and asked him for a shilling - and said, "What am I to do?" Wood has been living with a woman for nine years.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 26.</p>
